zboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bormwarrior>Borm Warrior</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mod in Kilt!</span><br>  Posts: 817<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/19/03 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3875.topic&index=21>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I don't have the heart to retype this...</span><hr size=1> Twelve years ago, after a long sleepless night, our 5-month-old baby died in my arms as I sat in our living room. I felt his spirit leave his body; it was as if someone had turned off a light switch. The poor boy had been born with only 3 of the 4 ventricles in his heart and not real arteries leading to his lungs. For five months he struggled for life, he was well enough to be home but not much else. He was very fussy, we surmised that he was always cold or otherwise uncomfortable but was too young to tell us.<br>
<br>
We had just recently been told that we should not expect him to see his first birthday. Up until that point the doctors had lied, either to us or to themselves, and suggested that he would need a heart transplant when he was 12, but otherwise we should just treat him normally. That one single cold doctor who dared to tell us the truth was the only thing that kept us from being completely shocked.<br>
<br>
We are grateful that we had him for 5 months. The point of this is not to make anyone else feel bad, but to let those going through it to know that the pain does decrease, but it never goes away. <br>
<br>
Some pointers for you Larry. In a few months the parents will be over the initial shock. Their pain will be increasing until then and at some point they may need a cathartic experience. You can be helpful there, if you are involved by just being present. You will not need to “fix” anything, just be compassionate. Secondly, every person they know will be too afraid to mention the child in the company of the parents. They know he is dead you cannot shock them. When people refuse to acknowledge that the child ever existed it is like he did not. Some time down the road ask to see pictures. Talk about the happy times you all had. Look at home videos with them. Send a card on his birthday, not a happy birthday card but a Remembering You card. The one person who ever did that for us made a huge impact on us.<br>
<br>
One year from the date he died take them to dinner and talk about him all night. You can all cry together. Otherwise they will be crying alone. I know.<br>
 <p>Warlord Borm, Veteran of Halas<br>
Member of Tribulation<br>
